Package com.rb.nonbiz.collections

Class RBEnumMapMergers

java.lang.Object
com.rb.nonbiz.collections.RBEnumMapMergers
public class RBEnumMapMergers
extends java.lang.Object
Various static utility methods that merge two or more RBEnumMaps.

The various methods have different expectations about inputs. E.g. you may want to throw if there is ever any key appearing in more than one input RBEnumMap.

    • mergeRBEnumMapsAllowingOverlapOnSimilarItemsOnly

      public static <E extends java.lang.Enum<E>,​ V> RBEnumMap<E,​V> mergeRBEnumMapsAllowingOverlapOnSimilarItemsOnly​(java.util.Iterator<RBEnumMap<E,​V>> mapsIterator, java.util.function.BiPredicate<V,​V> itemsAreSimilar)
      Merges a bunch of maps into a single one. Throws if a key appears in more than one map, unless the items we are trying to insert are 'similar' (based on the predicate passed in). Since this similarity is not the same as equality, this means that if e.g. the first map maps "A" to money(100), the second one (in the iterator) maps "A" to money(100 + 1e-9), and the third one to money(100 - 1e-9), and similarity is 'values similar to an epsilon of 1e-8', then the resulting map will show money(100) in the final value for "A", NOT money(100 + 1e-9) or money(100 - 1e-9)

    • mergeRBEnumMapsByValue

      @SafeVarargs public static <E extends java.lang.Enum<E>,​ V> RBEnumMap<E,​V> mergeRBEnumMapsByValue​(java.util.function.BinaryOperator<V> mergeFunction, RBEnumMap<E,​V> first, RBEnumMap<E,​V> second, RBEnumMap<E,​V>... rest)
      Merges a bunch of maps into a single one. In the event a key appears in more than one map, apply a binary operator (e.g. '+') to merge the values. This doesn't *assume* that the operator is commutative, but it probably should be. Otherwise, your result will depend on the order you pass the maps, which will be confusing.

    • mergeRBEnumMapsByValue

      public static <E extends java.lang.Enum<E>,​ V> RBEnumMap<E,​V> mergeRBEnumMapsByValue​(java.util.function.BinaryOperator<V> mergeFunction, java.util.function.UnaryOperator<V> onlyLeftPresent, java.util.function.UnaryOperator<V> onlyRightPresent, RBEnumMap<E,​V> leftMap, RBEnumMap<E,​V> rightMap)
      Merges two RBEnumMaps into a single one.

      For the 3 separate cases of a key appearing in the left map / right map / both maps, modify the values based on the functions passed in.

    • mergeRBEnumMapsByValue

      public static <E extends java.lang.Enum<E>,​ V> RBEnumMap<E,​V> mergeRBEnumMapsByValue​(java.util.function.BinaryOperator<V> mergeFunction, RBEnumMap<E,​V> leftMap, RBEnumMap<E,​V> rightMap)
      Merges two RBEnumMaps into a single one.

      If a key only appears in one of the maps, we copy the corresponding value. Otherwise we use the supplied merge function.

    • mergeRBEnumMapsByTransformedValue

      public static <E extends java.lang.Enum<E>,​ V1,​ V2> RBEnumMap<E,​V2> mergeRBEnumMapsByTransformedValue​(java.util.function.BiFunction<E,​java.util.List<V1>,​V2> mergeFunction, java.util.List<RBEnumMap<E,​V1>> mapsList)
      Merges a bunch of maps into a single one. This is similar to the previous overload, except that it allows you to merge multiple (and possibly 0) items at a time, plus the value in the returned map doesn't have to be of the same type as the input maps. This is particularly useful for cases where it is more computationally expensive (or numerically unstable) to merge N items 2 at a time (as with the previous overload) vs. merging them all together.

    • mergeRBEnumMapsByTransformedValue

      public static <E extends java.lang.Enum<E>,​ V1,​ V2,​ V3> RBEnumMap<E,​V3> mergeRBEnumMapsByTransformedValue​(java.util.function.BiFunction<V1,​V2,​V3> mergeFunction, java.util.function.Function<V1,​V3> onlyLeftPresent, java.util.function.Function<V2,​V3> onlyRightPresent, RBEnumMap<E,​V1> leftMap, RBEnumMap<E,​V2> rightMap)
      Merges two maps into a single one, but also transforms the values into a possibly different type. For the 3 separate cases of a key appearing in the left map / right map / both maps, modify the values based on the functions passed in.
      See Also:
      IidMapMergers.mergeIidMapsByTransformedEntry(com.rb.nonbiz.functional.TriFunction<com.rb.biz.types.asset.InstrumentId, V1, V2, V>, java.util.function.BiFunction<com.rb.biz.types.asset.InstrumentId, V1, V>, java.util.function.BiFunction<com.rb.biz.types.asset.InstrumentId, V2, V>, com.rb.nonbiz.collections.IidMap<V1>, com.rb.nonbiz.collections.IidMap<V2>)

    • mergeRBEnumMapsByValue

      public static <E extends java.lang.Enum<E>,​ V> RBEnumMap<E,​V> mergeRBEnumMapsByValue​(java.util.function.BinaryOperator<V> mergeFunction, java.util.stream.Stream<RBEnumMap<E,​V>> mapsStream)
      Merges a bunch of maps into a single one.

      In the event a key appears in more than one map, apply a binary operator (e.g. '+') to merge the values. This doesn't *assume* that the operator is commutative, but it probably should be. Otherwise, your result will depend on the order you pass the maps in the stream, which will be confusing.

    • dotProductOfRBEnumMaps

      public static <E extends java.lang.Enum<E>,​ V1 extends RBNumeric<? super V1>,​ V2 extends RBNumeric<? super V2>> double dotProductOfRBEnumMaps​(RBEnumMap<E,​V1> map1, RBEnumMap<E,​V2> map2)
      For two maps of RBNumeric, multiply each corresponding item, and return the sum of those terms, kind of like a vector dot product. The keys are expected to be the same in each map.
